            <b><font color="#000099" face="Arial" size="4">New Discussion</font></b>
            <FONT
            face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color=#000099 size=+1>
            <HR>
            </FONT>
            <P><font face="Arial" size="2"><a name="newdisc"></a><b><font color="#ff0000">Web Services with SOAP?</font></b></font>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">From: <a href="mailto:rc@trcs.com">Rajesh
            Chawla</a></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Hi folks,</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">I'm getting more and more into SOAP.
            It provides me with the ability to expose proprietary code in a
            relatively painless fashion using an XML standard that has the
            potential of working through a firewall.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">I'm very curious to hear if other
            folks are using SOAP or am I out on a limb again :-)</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Regards, Rajesh</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">[ Moderator Comment ]</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">SOAP stands for Simple Object Access
            Protocol and relates to the passing of messages between web service
            applications (remote procedure calls). It seems that SOAP is the
            dominant message protocol to emerge from several alternatives as it
            has been adopted by industry in the form of a W3C recommendation.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">A good reference for reading about
            SOAP is the W3C's Primer: <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/2002/CR-soap12-part0-20021219/">http://www.w3.org/TR/2002</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">~ Pete</font></p>
            <P>
            <a href="mailto:develop@adventive.com">
